panel discussion. So any difficult questions can go to these two gentlemen next to

60
00:03:32.420 --> 00:03:34.640
me. All right, over to you, Mark. Thank you.

61
00:03:34.670 --> 00:03:35.900
Yeah. Thanks a lot. It's great to be here.

62
00:03:37.200 --> 00:03:38.440
These are my disclosures.

63
00:03:39.960 --> 00:03:43.680
And really what I'm going to talk about today are the learnings from

64
00:03:45.300 --> 00:03:47.260
the use of PARP inhibitors in HRD cancer.

65
00:03:47.340 --> 00:03:50.980
So to date, it's the only successful example where synthetic

66
00:03:51.020 --> 00:03:52.470
lethality has actually

67
00:03:53.280 --> 00:03:55.280
been turned into cancer medicines.

68
00:03:56.920 --> 00:04:00.700
And obviously the original synthetic lethality approaches in Drosophila and then

69
00:04:00.740 --> 00:04:04.420
later yeast were genetic, where the impairment of two genes

70
00:04:04.460 --> 00:04:08.340
together leads to cell death, but where the impairment of either

71
00:04:08.380 --> 00:04:10.640
one alone is compatible with survival.

72
00:04:11.320 --> 00:04:14.420
Now, obviously, in cancer therapy, what we're doing is replacing one of those

73
00:04:14.460 --> 00:04:17.510
genetic components with a pharmacological inhibitor

74
00:04:18.820 --> 00:04:22.500
but still trying to exploit a tumor-specific deficiency.

75
00:04:24.340 --> 00:04:28.140
And the DNA damage response, so DDR, has really been the focus of

76
00:04:28.200 --> 00:04:31.380
much of the synthetic lethality approaches so far,

77
00:04:31.980 --> 00:04:33.840
primarily because it's a hallmark of cancer.

78
00:04:33.860 --> 00:04:37.520
And essentially, every cancer will have lost one or more DDR

79
00:04:37.540 --> 00:04:38.240
capability,

80
00:04:39.220 --> 00:04:42.740
coupled with the fact that there are multiple pathways that deal with different

81
00:04:42.780 --> 00:04:46.600
types of damage, and you can have a scenario in

82
00:04:46.660 --> 00:04:50.440
DDR where the loss of one DDR capability can at least be compensated

83
00:04:50.500 --> 00:04:54.100
for by another pathway. So in terms of

84
00:04:54.620 --> 00:04:58.460
trying to exploit that with inhibitors, on the right, what you

85
00:04:58.500 --> 00:05:02.400
can see here is essentially a scenario where two DDR

86
00:05:02.440 --> 00:05:06.420
pathways, A and B, have the potential to compensate for each other, and where

87
00:05:06.460 --> 00:05:10.260
in the cancer where it's lost pathway A and is now dependent on B, we

88
00:05:10.340 --> 00:05:13.620
can target that with a small molecule inhibitor and induce cancer cell death.

89
00:05:14.520 --> 00:05:17.960
Whereas in the normal tissue, there would still be pathway A to provide that

90
00:05:18.020 --> 00:05:18.760
compensation.

91
00:05:20.720 --> 00:05:24.100
So I'm showing here on the left and the right essentially DDR,

92
00:05:25.140 --> 00:05:28.610
where you have multiple different types of damage, and you have different pathways

93
00:05:28.640 --> 00:05:32.350
that can deal with that. For example, one of the most common

94
00:05:32.400 --> 00:05:36.060
forms of DNA damage is single-strand breaks, tens of thousands every day per cell.

95
00:05:37.020 --> 00:05:40.040
And the base excision repair pathway will deal with that, where PARP is involved.

96
00:05:40.760 --> 00:05:42.840
And the most cytotoxic

97
00:05:43.860 --> 00:05:45.860
form of DNA damage, DNA double-strand breaks.

98
00:05:45.920 --> 00:05:48.460
You can see there are multiple pathways to try and deal with that.

99
00:05:48.560 --> 00:05:51.940
So in an ideal scenario, if you have a replicated

100
00:05:51.980 --> 00:05:55.720
DNA sister chromatid, you can use that as an undamaged template.

101
00:05:55.760 --> 00:05:58.420
It's accurate. It's efficient. And then there are also

102
00:05:59.600 --> 00:06:02.380
error-prone pathways, microhomology end joining,

103
00:06:03.360 --> 00:06:07.008
and non-homologous end joining.And it's really important that

104
00:06:07.188 --> 00:06:10.948
during the cell cycle, there's an opportunity to try and repair the damage

105
00:06:10.988 --> 00:06:14.578
before going into the next phase. So we know that cancers will

106
00:06:14.608 --> 00:06:18.468
essentially have all lost a G1S checkpoint capability.

107
00:06:18.968 --> 00:06:21.948
So there's a greater dependency in cancers on the intra-S

108
00:06:22.968 --> 00:06:26.148
checkpoints and also their G2M and intra-M

109
00:06:26.768 --> 00:06:30.198
checkpoints as well. And if we look at the DDR proteins that have

110
00:06:30.248 --> 00:06:34.128
primarily been the focus of small molecule inhibitor approaches,

111
00:06:34.688 --> 00:06:38.128
you can see that that includes PARP, which has a role in both single-strand break

112
00:06:38.168 --> 00:06:41.768
and double-strand break, but also ATM, ATR, Pol Q or Pol

113
00:06:41.848 --> 00:06:45.048
theta, which is involved in MMEJ. And you can see

114
00:06:45.608 --> 00:06:48.868
roles for ATR in intra-S phase, but also importantly, these

115
00:06:49.508 --> 00:06:53.308
potential targets, BRCA1 and WE1, that are involved in the G2M checkpoint.

116
00:06:54.568 --> 00:06:58.288
Now, early indications were that DDR dependencies

117
00:06:58.928 --> 00:06:59.748
could be targeted.

118
00:07:00.748 --> 00:07:03.698
Some of the very early work came from Steve Jackson's work with Simon Bolton,

119
00:07:04.068 --> 00:07:07.508
carried out this experiment. And here what you can see is sensitivity

120
00:07:07.608 --> 00:07:09.167
to radiation treatment.

121
00:07:10.868 --> 00:07:14.728
You don't have a huge increase in sensitization if you knock out NHEJ,

122
00:07:15.048 --> 00:07:17.628
the Ligase IV or Ku70 proteins in yeast.

123
00:07:18.098 --> 00:07:21.298
There's a greater dependency on RAD52, which is involved in homologous

124
00:07:21.348 --> 00:07:24.728
recombination repair in yeast. But you can see that if you take out both

125
00:07:26.148 --> 00:07:29.808
the HR and the NHEJ, you get a significant

126
00:07:29.828 --> 00:07:31.458
increase in sensitization.

127
00:07:32.408 --> 00:07:35.208
And some of the early work that was done in Steve's lab with Rebecca Isard and

128
00:07:35.228 --> 00:07:35.808
Graham Smith

129
00:07:36.868 --> 00:07:40.528
demonstrated you could identify and use inhibitors of DDR

130
00:07:40.568 --> 00:07:42.828
proteins in order to generate sensitization.

131
00:07:44.128 --> 00:07:47.588
And as Tim mentioned, that led to the formation of the very first company to focus

132
00:07:47.648 --> 00:07:49.928
on targeting DDR in cancer, which was Kudos.

133
00:07:50.908 --> 00:07:53.368
And you can see actually how young we really were then.

134
00:07:54.648 --> 00:07:56.368
So Graham looks a bit younger too.

135
00:07:57.468 --> 00:08:01.268
He's now the CSO of RTS, and Neil Smith went on to be the CEO of RTS.

136
00:08:03.628 --> 00:08:07.588
So it was really a collaboration between Kudos, who at that

137
00:08:07.668 --> 00:08:11.348
time had generated pro PARP inhibitors, and Alan Ashworth's group at

138
00:08:12.048 --> 00:08:15.357
the ICR that led to this discovery,

139
00:08:16.208 --> 00:08:20.048
co-discovery I should say, of the sensitivity of

140
00:08:20.628 --> 00:08:22.528
BRCA deficient cells to PARP inhibitors.

141
00:08:22.608 --> 00:08:26.368
So, back-to-back publications from Kudos and Ashworth

142
00:08:26.448 --> 00:08:30.328
lab, and also Nicola Curtin in Newcastle and Thomas Helleday

143
00:08:31.268 --> 00:08:33.948
in Sheffield. And basically what you can see here

144
00:08:34.808 --> 00:08:38.308
are mouse ES cells that are knocked out for BRCA2 are incredibly sensitive to PARP

145
00:08:38.348 --> 00:08:39.148
inhibitor treatment.

146
00:08:39.989 --> 00:08:43.828
But importantly, wild type cells are very resistant to that.

147
00:08:43.869 --> 00:08:47.238
And in fact, even cells that have a single functional copy

148
00:08:47.808 --> 00:08:51.308
of BRCA2 are very resistant. Now, that's important because

149
00:08:51.468 --> 00:08:52.988
BRCA1 or BRCA2 mutations

150
00:08:54.248 --> 00:08:58.048
can be inherited. And in those patients that have a very high risk of cancer, if

151
00:08:58.068 --> 00:09:01.848
they have a BRCA mutation that's been inherited, they will have a single

152
00:09:01.948 --> 00:09:05.448
functional copy in all of their normal cells in the body, and only the tumor will

153
00:09:05.468 --> 00:09:08.888
have lost that second copy and therefore demonstrate a

154
00:09:08.928 --> 00:09:12.568
sensitivity. So the potential for a large therapeutic window was really

155
00:09:12.588 --> 00:09:13.108
important.

156
00:09:14.048 --> 00:09:14.868
And so at the time,

157
00:09:15.808 --> 00:09:19.788
the mechanism that we were thinking about was that inhibitors like

158
00:09:19.828 --> 00:09:23.788
olaparib could prevent PARP from repairing those single-strand breaks.

159
00:09:24.628 --> 00:09:28.008
Then when those single-strand breaks were encountered by a replication fork, you

160
00:09:28.028 --> 00:09:30.038
would end up getting a one-ended DNA double-strand break.

161
00:09:30.628 --> 00:09:33.218
In normal cells, that would be repaired by homologous recombination.

162
00:09:34.208 --> 00:09:38.008
But in HR deficient cells or HRD cancer cells, such as BRCA

163
00:09:38.028 --> 00:09:41.968
mutated cancers, they would end up having to use error-prone pathways like

164
00:09:42.068 --> 00:09:45.768
NHEJ, and that would drive genomic instability and ultimately cancer specific cell

165
00:09:45.808 --> 00:09:46.068
death.

166
00:09:47.358 --> 00:09:51.248
And in fact, the phase one expansion cohort for

167
00:09:51.288 --> 00:09:51.808
olaparib

168
00:09:52.748 --> 00:09:54.888
went on to test that hypothesis in the clinic.

169
00:09:54.918 --> 00:09:58.868
And what I'm showing is the very first patient who responded to olaparib

170
00:09:58.928 --> 00:10:01.448
single agent. It was an ovarian cancer patient.

171
00:10:01.488 --> 00:10:04.748
You can see the peritoneal mass reduces over a number of months.

172
00:10:05.358 --> 00:10:07.968
And it was quite unusual for a phase one trial to be published in The New England

173
00:10:08.008 --> 00:10:11.208
Journal of Medicine. But the reason for that is that this was the very first

174
00:10:11.268 --> 00:10:13.688
example of synthetic lethality demonstrated in the clinic.

175
00:10:15.728 --> 00:10:19.468
And olaparib went on to be approved in multiple different

176
00:10:19.748 --> 00:10:23.188
tumor types and lines of therapy. But this is just to show you an example in

177
00:10:23.248 --> 00:10:26.708
the first-line ovarian cancer

178
00:10:26.748 --> 00:10:30.128
patients who've been treated with carboplatin

179
00:10:30.288 --> 00:10:32.788
paclitaxel, then olaparib maintenance or placebo.

180
00:10:32.818 --> 00:10:36.658
And you can see that that PARP inhibitor treatment has made a massive

181
00:10:36.728 --> 00:10:38.788
difference in terms of progression-free survival.

182
00:10:40.468 --> 00:10:42.068
And there are now four

183
00:10:42.948 --> 00:10:45.128
first-generation PARP inhibitors with global approval.

184
00:10:45.268 --> 00:10:49.128
So niraparib, rucaparib, and talazoparib, as well as olaparib in five tumor

185
00:10:49.188 --> 00:10:50.568
types as shown here.

186
00:10:53.248 --> 00:10:57.208
So although I think we can be really proud of the

187
00:10:57.248 --> 00:11:00.888
science that went into this and ultimately those

188
00:11:00.928 --> 00:11:04.908
treatments for patients, there are still key questions to be addressed for

189
00:11:04.948 --> 00:11:06.308
PARP inhibitor synthetic lethality.

190
00:11:07.088 --> 00:11:08.168
So for example, why don't

191
00:11:09.028 --> 00:11:11.668
PARP inhibitors work in all tumors with HR deficiency?

192
00:11:12.568 --> 00:11:16.508
Why doesn't the PARP knockout reproduce the PARP inhibitor synthetic lethality

193
00:11:16.528 --> 00:11:20.068
in HRD cells? And why do different PARP inhibitors

194
00:11:20.108 --> 00:11:22.168
demonstrate different levels of monotherapy activity?

195
00:11:23.268 --> 00:11:26.618
So what I'd like to do for the rest of the talk is highlight some of the insights

196
00:11:26.648 --> 00:11:27.068
we've gained

197
00:11:28.028 --> 00:11:31.508
in addressing those questions and how that may help as we go forward to think about

198
00:11:31.608 --> 00:11:33.328
other synthetic lethal approaches

199
00:11:35.568 --> 00:11:37.908
in trying to generate new treatments for cancer.

200
00:11:39.168 --> 00:11:42.728
So this is an analysis of

201
00:11:42.768 --> 00:11:46.448
multiple different CRISPR screens that was carried out by Joseph Formant and his

202
00:11:46.488 --> 00:11:50.328
team at AstraZeneca. And essentially what they identified was

203
00:11:50.408 --> 00:11:51.548
110

204
00:11:52.568 --> 00:11:54.568
PARP inhibitor sensitizer genes.

205
00:11:57.068 --> 00:12:00.688
And that obviously includes what you would expect, HR genes such as

206
00:12:00.708 --> 00:12:03.768
BRCA1, BRCA2, PALB2, and the RAD51 paralogs.

207
00:12:04.328 --> 00:12:07.768
It also included DDR genes not directly involved in

208
00:12:07.808 --> 00:12:10.188
HRAnd it also involved

209
00:12:11.388 --> 00:12:15.008
other genes involved in different aspects of biology that could impact on HR

210
00:12:15.048 --> 00:12:17.428
repair, such as the chromatin cohesion genes.

211
00:12:18.828 --> 00:12:22.048
So these argue that the activity of PARP inhibitors could go beyond

212
00:12:22.888 --> 00:12:23.708
HR deficiency.

213
00:12:24.648 --> 00:12:27.988
But the question was really, do all deficiencies give similar levels of PARP

214
00:12:28.008 --> 00:12:30.708
inhibitor sensitivity? And the answer to that is no.

215
00:12:31.128 --> 00:12:34.938
And in fact, even within BRCA genes themselves, different

216
00:12:34.988 --> 00:12:38.968
mutations can give you different outcomes to PARP inhibitor treatment.

217
00:12:39.558 --> 00:12:41.768
So you can see here a wild-type BRCA cell.

218
00:12:41.808 --> 00:12:42.928
This is in Jos Jonkers'

219
00:12:44.468 --> 00:12:48.128
genetically engineered knockout mouse, where we've put back either a wild

220
00:12:48.208 --> 00:12:51.928
type or a deleted version of BRCA1 or a

221
00:12:52.008 --> 00:12:53.368
C61G mutant,

222
00:12:54.188 --> 00:12:57.968
which is a ring domain mutation that still means that BRCA has

223
00:12:58.008 --> 00:12:59.388
retained some of that activity.

224
00:13:00.337 --> 00:13:03.748
And what you can see is that the deleted version is giving you long-term

225
00:13:03.948 --> 00:13:05.728
responses in those animals.

226
00:13:06.588 --> 00:13:10.528
But interestingly, the C61G mutation, which is a hypomorph, is

227
00:13:10.588 --> 00:13:14.528
not as effective. And what we believe is that you have some residual

228
00:13:14.628 --> 00:13:15.688
activity of BRCA,

229
00:13:16.588 --> 00:13:18.388
which can modify the PARP response.

230
00:13:18.428 --> 00:13:18.868
But also,

231
00:13:19.868 --> 00:13:20.868
you will either have

232
00:13:22.388 --> 00:13:26.028
a lack of an ability to get certain types of reversion mutations or,

233
00:13:26.548 --> 00:13:28.768
in this case, maybe it's more easy to get those reversion

234
00:13:28.788 --> 00:13:32.388
mutations. So we've gone on to look at

235
00:13:33.048 --> 00:13:35.408
lots of different players within homologous recombination.

236
00:13:35.428 --> 00:13:36.708
It's a very complex pathway,

237
00:13:37.628 --> 00:13:40.928
and it's very difficult to just look at different cell lines which might have one

238
00:13:40.988 --> 00:13:44.928
deficiency. It's really important to try and do isogenic analysis to try and tease

239
00:13:45.048 --> 00:13:47.038
out relative levels of sensitivity.

240
00:13:47.708 --> 00:13:51.528
It's also interesting that a single cell line is not going to be possible to

241
00:13:51.588 --> 00:13:55.008
knock out every HR gene. So for example, in the

242
00:13:55.088 --> 00:13:59.048
DU145 cell line, we can knock out BRCA1, but we couldn't knock

243
00:13:59.148 --> 00:14:02.348
out BRCA2. It wasn't viable, and vice versa for SKOV3.

244
00:14:02.888 --> 00:14:06.448
But together, what Joseph and the team were able to do is essentially

245
00:14:06.508 --> 00:14:07.368
identify those

246
00:14:08.408 --> 00:14:12.088
HR genes with the highest level of PARP inhibitor sensitivity, BRCA1, BRCA2,

247
00:14:12.188 --> 00:14:16.168
PALB2, XLCC3, and RAD51C. Whereas others, such as

248
00:14:16.248 --> 00:14:19.927
RAD51B and RAD54L, for example, are not giving you the same level of

249
00:14:19.968 --> 00:14:23.518
sensitivity. An ATM deficiency is giving you some sort of intermediate level of

250
00:14:23.568 --> 00:14:24.208
sensitivity.

251
00:14:25.988 --> 00:14:29.268
But ultimately, what we really want to try and do is understand functionality

252
00:14:31.568 --> 00:14:35.108
of HR pathway status. And so RAD51

253
00:14:35.188 --> 00:14:39.118
foci will form during repair, so you can monitor those at

254
00:14:39.128 --> 00:14:41.848
the basal level, and that will look something like this.

255
00:14:41.908 --> 00:14:45.428
So these are the data from Violeta Serra when she was at Vall d'Hebron in

256
00:14:45.448 --> 00:14:49.188
Barcelona. And essentially, she used RAD51

257
00:14:49.198 --> 00:14:52.488
foci to look at the correlation with PARP inhibitor sensitivity.

258
00:14:53.608 --> 00:14:57.228
So this is probably one of the largest patient-derived expand model cohorts

259
00:14:57.928 --> 00:14:59.868
to be studied for PARP inhibitor response.

260
00:14:59.888 --> 00:15:02.428
And you can see that all of those

261
00:15:03.248 --> 00:15:06.818
tumors that showed regression had some form of HR

262
00:15:06.988 --> 00:15:09.728
alteration, and they also had

263
00:15:10.668 --> 00:15:12.628
very low levels of RAD51 foci.

264
00:15:13.548 --> 00:15:16.128
You can see in those tumors that did not respond

265
00:15:17.208 --> 00:15:20.888
that they might have had an alteration, but actually RAD51 foci is

266
00:15:21.248 --> 00:15:24.188
being expressed here. We can see that RAD51 foci expression

267
00:15:24.968 --> 00:15:28.568
indicating that there's likely to have been a reactivation of the pathway.

268
00:15:29.048 --> 00:15:32.028
And in fact, that's what we're seeing when you start to analyze

269
00:15:33.388 --> 00:15:35.088
the mechanisms behind that resistance.

270
00:15:35.128 --> 00:15:38.437
And so more than 90% of PARP inhibitor-resistant models,

271
00:15:38.768 --> 00:15:41.968
essentially, depending on or independently of their mechanism, will actually

272
00:15:42.028 --> 00:15:45.848
reactivate HR function, and you'll see RAD51 foci.

273
00:15:47.548 --> 00:15:51.388
So I think these data really show that PARP inhibitor response is linked to HRD,

274
00:15:51.828 --> 00:15:55.388
but there can be a variability of response and that different levels of innate

275
00:15:55.468 --> 00:15:59.288
sensitivity can modify that response, as can the likelihood of

276
00:15:59.308 --> 00:16:00.228
acquired resistance.

277
00:16:01.928 --> 00:16:03.048
And the second question, why

278
00:16:04.088 --> 00:16:07.568
doesn't PARP knockout reproduce the PARP inhibitor

279
00:16:07.988 --> 00:16:11.948
HRD synthetic lethality? Very early on, we'd identified a sort of

280
00:16:11.988 --> 00:16:15.518
anomaly, if you like, which was we'd identified synthetic lethality with the

281
00:16:15.548 --> 00:16:17.248
inhibitor. But when we looked at a

282
00:16:18.208 --> 00:16:18.768
cell line

283
00:16:20.848 --> 00:16:24.738
sort of cohort of just under 100 cell lines, what we saw when we were looking at

284
00:16:24.828 --> 00:16:28.407
PARP inhibitor sensitivity was that those cells that had higher levels

285
00:16:28.508 --> 00:16:32.208
of PARP protein expression could either be sensitive to

286
00:16:32.248 --> 00:16:32.648
olaparib,

287
00:16:33.608 --> 00:16:36.308
so low GI50s, or they could be insensitive.

288
00:16:37.128 --> 00:16:40.628
But those cancer cell lines that had low levels of PARP1

289
00:16:40.668 --> 00:16:42.168
invariably were not sensitive.

290
00:16:43.328 --> 00:16:47.028
So this argued that you did need the protein to be present to get the sensitivity.

291
00:16:48.248 --> 00:16:51.768
And really it was the work of Yves Pommier's group in 2012 that

292
00:16:51.828 --> 00:16:55.728
also cemented that and showed that PARP inhibitors can

293
00:16:55.788 --> 00:16:58.428
actually increase the trapping of PARP1 on chromatin.

294
00:16:58.857 --> 00:17:02.468
And so now we have a modification of the mechanism whereby PARP trapping

295
00:17:03.068 --> 00:17:06.969
essentially is important. And if PARP is still trapped

296
00:17:07.008 --> 00:17:09.868
on the DNA when the replication fork reaches it, you end up

297
00:17:10.788 --> 00:17:14.709
ultimately getting a DNA double-strand break, and then you again have the

298
00:17:14.729 --> 00:17:17.408
scenario of HRD versus normal cell repair.

299
00:17:19.808 --> 00:17:23.048
So there have been some questions about the importance of PARP trapping even as

300
00:17:23.068 --> 00:17:24.348
recently as a couple of years ago.

301
00:17:25.668 --> 00:17:29.408
I think the clinical data seem to be consistent with that in the sense that

302
00:17:29.428 --> 00:17:33.028
rucaparib, which is a poor trapper, was not shown to have monotherapy activity in a

303
00:17:33.048 --> 00:17:36.838
clinic. Talazoparib and olaparib,

304
00:17:36.888 --> 00:17:40.718
niraparib, and rucaparib all had sort of PARP trapping capability and showed

305
00:17:40.728 --> 00:17:44.408
monotherapy activity. But really, I think it was only very

306
00:17:44.468 --> 00:17:48.268
recently where we published this paper in NAR that we were able to

307
00:17:48.328 --> 00:17:52.308
find a PARP1 mutation that provided separation of

308
00:17:52.348 --> 00:17:55.628
function between polyrelation inhibition observations and PARP

309
00:17:55.668 --> 00:17:59.278
trapping. So if you look at sarucaparib, which is one of the PARP1

310
00:17:59.428 --> 00:18:00.888
selective agents,

311
00:18:01.948 --> 00:18:03.948
it's a much stronger trapper than olaparib.

312
00:18:05.428 --> 00:18:08.028
And what you see interestingly is that that PARP

313
00:18:08.068 --> 00:18:11.888
trappingDNA damage, genomic instability, and cell kill are

314
00:18:11.908 --> 00:18:15.868
all sort of linked, and in BRCA2-deficient cells, they're higher.

315
00:18:15.948 --> 00:18:19.228
So you can see a greater sensitivity in a BRCA2

316
00:18:19.688 --> 00:18:23.328
isogenic knockout. You can see greater levels of PARP trapping, and that

317
00:18:23.388 --> 00:18:27.268
correlates with greater levels of double-strand break formation based on

318
00:18:27.288 --> 00:18:30.568
γH2AX and on genomic instability based on

319
00:18:30.588 --> 00:18:31.408
micronuclei.

320
00:18:33.008 --> 00:18:35.248
And in two independent clones in a sort of

321
00:18:36.068 --> 00:18:39.608
experiment where we were trying to generate resistance, what we found was

322
00:18:39.648 --> 00:18:43.508
that two resistant clones also then had lost

323
00:18:44.268 --> 00:18:46.008
the ability for SERPs to trap.

324
00:18:46.848 --> 00:18:50.568
And that mutation, L77P, is in the helical domain of

325
00:18:50.608 --> 00:18:53.048
PARP1, which is involved in stabilizing DNA binding.

326
00:18:54.248 --> 00:18:57.828
So this was some really nice evidence that resistance could

327
00:18:57.868 --> 00:18:59.908
be correlated with a loss of trapping.

328
00:19:00.328 --> 00:19:03.708
But I think what was even more convincing is it has the opposite effect on

329
00:19:03.728 --> 00:19:06.668
veliparib. So veliparib is normally not a very potent

330
00:19:08.608 --> 00:19:11.068
cell killer of BRCA-deficient cells.

331
00:19:11.128 --> 00:19:14.528
But what you can see is in that PARP1 mutation setting,

332
00:19:15.008 --> 00:19:17.268
you've increased the efficacy of veliparib

333
00:19:18.188 --> 00:19:21.848
in this model, and you can see that correlating with that, you see greater levels

334
00:19:21.908 --> 00:19:25.688
of trapping. And you're not seeing actually greater levels of

335
00:19:25.708 --> 00:19:27.628
polyolation inhibition. If anything, it's slightly worse.

336
00:19:28.108 --> 00:19:30.708
So this is the first time we've separated polyolation

337
00:19:31.848 --> 00:19:35.188
inhibition from trapping. So I think these data, at least

338
00:19:35.788 --> 00:19:37.968
as far as we're concerned, really provides

339
00:19:38.908 --> 00:19:42.368
strong indication that trapping is really important for monotherapy activity.

340
00:19:44.088 --> 00:19:46.068
So why do PARP inhibitors demonstrate

341
00:19:47.808 --> 00:19:51.008
different levels of monotherapy activity? Because that's certainly been seen.

342
00:19:51.068 --> 00:19:52.048
If we look at the long-term

343
00:19:53.048 --> 00:19:56.288
survival of ovarian cancer patients in first line,

344
00:19:56.848 --> 00:20:00.748
olaparib has a ratio of less than one, but rucaparib and niraparib

345
00:20:01.068 --> 00:20:02.628
has a ratio of greater than one.

346
00:20:03.428 --> 00:20:07.108
And so what's the basis behind that if we want to learn, for

347
00:20:07.168 --> 00:20:10.648
example, about the next generation PARP inhibitors and how we might improve them?

348
00:20:10.708 --> 00:20:14.528
So one of the things that we observed is that there's a very steep cutoff

349
00:20:14.628 --> 00:20:15.088
between

350
00:20:16.148 --> 00:20:18.628
PARP inhibitor dose and tumor regression.

351
00:20:18.908 --> 00:20:22.748
So in this experiment in a XenTech HBCX10 model, what you

352
00:20:22.788 --> 00:20:26.208
can see is that 25 mg per kg of olaparib can't get the tumor under control,

353
00:20:26.708 --> 00:20:28.808
but the 50 mg per kg and the 100 mg per kg can.

354
00:20:28.868 --> 00:20:31.268
So these are the averages of 10 independent tumors.

355
00:20:32.328 --> 00:20:36.248
If you look at polyolation inhibition, what you see is that all of, and it's very

356
00:20:36.288 --> 00:20:40.008
hard to see because it just goes straight down initially, but

357
00:20:40.028 --> 00:20:42.848
essentially all of the doses will completely inhibit PARP.

358
00:20:44.288 --> 00:20:48.088
So you basically have polyolation inhibition in all of the cases, and it's about

359
00:20:48.128 --> 00:20:51.848
really the recovery of that polyolation and therefore PARP

360
00:20:51.908 --> 00:20:53.468
activity that seems to be important.

361
00:20:53.988 --> 00:20:56.568
And you can see that you get faster recovery with the lower doses.

362
00:20:57.068 --> 00:21:00.928
And if we look at the time above the IC50, IC90,

363
00:21:00.988 --> 00:21:04.558
IC95, so the closer you get to 100% inhibition and the time over that,

364
00:21:04.968 --> 00:21:08.918
you see the biggest differences between an active dose at 50 mg and an inactive

365
00:21:08.988 --> 00:21:12.008
dose effectively at 25 mg. So you can see that here.

366
00:21:12.068 --> 00:21:15.908
So the trend is towards complete inhibition of PARP correlating

367
00:21:16.528 --> 00:21:19.148
with tumor shrinkage and efficacy.

368
00:21:19.588 --> 00:21:20.708
And a very talented

369
00:21:21.808 --> 00:21:22.088
modeler,

370
00:21:23.028 --> 00:21:26.628
James Yates, when he was at AstraZeneca, came up with this

371
00:21:26.688 --> 00:21:30.528
mathematical model looking at the relationship between polyolation

372
00:21:30.568 --> 00:21:33.488
inhibition and the number of predicted single-strand breaks.

373
00:21:34.098 --> 00:21:37.588
And what he saw was this, a biphasic scenario where really only when you get past

374
00:21:37.768 --> 00:21:41.448
90% to 95% inhibition, do you see this big increase in predicted breaks.

375
00:21:41.508 --> 00:21:44.728
And for many years, we weren't able to really demonstrate that

376
00:21:44.768 --> 00:21:45.688
directly

377
00:21:46.688 --> 00:21:49.168
in the lab until we were able to utilize

378
00:21:49.968 --> 00:21:52.648
IntoDNA's STRIDE technology, which quantifies

379
00:21:53.528 --> 00:21:55.168
either single-strand breaks or double-strand breaks.

380
00:21:55.228 --> 00:21:58.838
And what you can see essentially is that same biphasic relationship that we were

381
00:21:58.908 --> 00:21:59.808
able to demonstrate

382
00:22:00.928 --> 00:22:03.068
and that we'd seen in the mathematical model.

383
00:22:04.368 --> 00:22:08.088
So that argues you've got to try and get almost complete inhibition

384
00:22:08.368 --> 00:22:08.808
of PARP.

385
00:22:09.728 --> 00:22:13.608
What does it mean in terms of duration of treatment scheduling?

386
00:22:14.208 --> 00:22:17.708
Well, these experiments, long-term experiments in the same HBCX10 model,

387
00:22:18.428 --> 00:22:19.468
show that if you give

388
00:22:20.588 --> 00:22:24.368
olaparib at the clinical equivalent dose of 100 mg per kg

389
00:22:24.868 --> 00:22:25.248
daily

390
00:22:26.268 --> 00:22:28.188
for 100 days, you don't get any tumors

391
00:22:29.168 --> 00:22:33.148
escaping on treatment. But if you halve that dose or you give that

392
00:22:33.268 --> 00:22:37.128
same high dose intermittently, what you see is that you're now getting tumors

393
00:22:37.168 --> 00:22:40.988
escaping on treatment, and that correlated with a greater residual

394
00:22:41.508 --> 00:22:45.328
tumor volume. So in those scenarios, you had nearly 10%

395
00:22:45.888 --> 00:22:49.368
residual tumor versus only 1.5% for the high

396
00:22:49.708 --> 00:22:53.248
continuous dosing. So what we think this means is that you're more likely to have

397
00:22:53.268 --> 00:22:55.008
tumor cells that can become resistant.

398
00:22:55.488 --> 00:22:59.308
What we know about resistance reactivation of HRR, that will also

399
00:22:59.368 --> 00:23:03.268
impact on subsequent treatments such as platinum treatment

400
00:23:03.328 --> 00:23:05.168
or topoisomerase treatment in the clinic.

401
00:23:07.028 --> 00:23:10.848
So we've looked at the different first-generation PARP

402
00:23:10.868 --> 00:23:14.568
inhibitors to try and understand what it is that might drive that long-term

403
00:23:14.608 --> 00:23:18.528
efficacy. And really what we've seen is obviously differences

404
00:23:18.548 --> 00:23:22.428
in trapping that I mentioned. Importantly, differences in the

405
00:23:22.448 --> 00:23:26.028
primary pharmacology that lead to different windows between HRD

406
00:23:26.428 --> 00:23:29.288
and HR proficiency. So rucaparib and olaparib have

407
00:23:30.128 --> 00:23:33.188
wide windows. Niraparib, talazoparib, more narrow windows.

408
00:23:33.228 --> 00:23:37.128
You can see talazoparib is shifted to the left because it's very potent in terms

409
00:23:37.168 --> 00:23:38.108
of cytotoxicity.

410
00:23:39.068 --> 00:23:41.168
But also secondary pharmacology is quite different.

411
00:23:41.508 --> 00:23:43.008
So talazoparib and olaparib have clean

412
00:23:44.188 --> 00:23:48.028
secondary pharmacologies. Niraparib and rucaparib hit quite a lot of other

413
00:23:48.048 --> 00:23:49.768
things that can lead to

414
00:23:50.608 --> 00:23:53.608
the side effects that are specific for those agents.

415
00:23:53.638 --> 00:23:56.708
So hypertension, increased liver enzymes, insomnia, and so on.

416
00:23:57.548 --> 00:24:01.008
And if we look at the safety profiles in the Phase III trials,

417
00:24:01.568 --> 00:24:05.388
Grade 3 or 4, what you can see is that that is different between the different

418
00:24:05.428 --> 00:24:09.108
PARP inhibitors. And the important bit that I want us to focus on really is the

419
00:24:09.188 --> 00:24:13.168
higherNow, percentage of patients that had to have dose reductions

420
00:24:13.188 --> 00:24:16.668
as interruptions. So if we think back to the preclinical models, what it's telling

421
00:24:16.708 --> 00:24:19.988
us is you don't want to have that. You want to give high doses continuously if you

422
00:24:20.028 --> 00:24:23.768
can. If tolerability interferes with that, then that is going to potentially impact

423
00:24:24.328 --> 00:24:25.687
on the long-term patient outcome.

424
00:24:26.988 --> 00:24:29.028
So I'm going to summarize now what we've learned.

425
00:24:29.728 --> 00:24:30.448
So first of all,

426
00:24:31.348 --> 00:24:35.328
DDR represents a good opportunity for synthetic lethality based cancer therapies

427
00:24:35.408 --> 00:24:38.948
due to loss of function and the resulting targetable dependencies.

428
00:24:41.028 --> 00:24:44.568
Just a word of caution, not all synthetic lethal opportunities will be detected by

429
00:24:45.008 --> 00:24:47.858
gene knockout in a deficient background, and we should be doing

430
00:24:48.448 --> 00:24:51.988
inhibitor screens as well to try and identify examples where

431
00:24:52.048 --> 00:24:53.888
that might give you the synthetic lethality.

432
00:24:54.828 --> 00:24:57.128
And that target identification is only the first step really.

433
00:24:57.468 --> 00:25:00.417
Success is going to require a synthetic lethal target with a potential wide

434
00:25:00.428 --> 00:25:04.008
therapeutic index, inhibitors with clean pharmacology, specificity and

435
00:25:04.048 --> 00:25:07.548
potency, and an understanding of the level of target engagement that's required.

436
00:25:08.488 --> 00:25:11.368
Degraders, for example, may need to give close to knockout levels.

437
00:25:11.468 --> 00:25:15.248
We had a DNPH1 scenario where the knockout had been published

438
00:25:15.528 --> 00:25:19.148
to give part of the sensitivity. We used inhibitors and PROTACs.

439
00:25:19.568 --> 00:25:22.408
With the PROTACs, we were nearly getting 95% or more

440
00:25:22.468 --> 00:25:24.948
inhibition of protein expression.

441
00:25:25.188 --> 00:25:27.468
But we still couldn't phenocopy the knockout.

442
00:25:28.528 --> 00:25:32.128
And then finally, an understanding of the quality and quality tools for effective

443
00:25:32.168 --> 00:25:34.388
patient selection is going to be important, and I think you'll hear more about that

444
00:25:35.308 --> 00:25:36.028
from Tim. So,

445
00:25:37.888 --> 00:25:41.328
I'd just like to thank my ESAC colleagues and all of our collaborators in the past

446
00:25:41.988 --> 00:25:44.288
for their work that's contributed to this talk today. Thank you.

447
00:25:52.068 --> 00:25:55.828
Thanks very much, Mark. Fantastic talk as always.

448
00:25:56.628 --> 00:26:00.268
There are plenty of seats in front, actually, so please come and

449
00:26:01.148 --> 00:26:02.228
fill up all the seats there.

450
00:26:03.628 --> 00:26:04.788
It's great to see a

451
00:26:05.728 --> 00:26:09.568
really packed room here, really does show the interest in synthetic lethality.

452
00:26:10.808 --> 00:26:14.368
Just looking at all of the old photographs from Mark and Graham

453
00:26:14.448 --> 00:26:16.768
Smith and Steve Jackson,

454
00:26:17.828 --> 00:26:21.628
it did bring back memories because I think the first time I met Mark was when

455
00:26:22.848 --> 00:26:26.428
I was still at the Royal Marsden, and Mark was still at Kudos, and we were

456
00:26:26.468 --> 00:26:28.088
preparing slides for ASCO.

457
00:26:29.768 --> 00:26:31.588
I shouldn't say ASCO at this meeting, but yeah.

458
00:26:31.808 --> 00:26:35.368
This was back in 2006, 2007 time. But

459
00:26:35.888 --> 00:26:38.308
that's 20 years ago, Mark. That's a whole lifetime. Wow.

460
00:26:38.358 --> 00:26:39.368
And we don't look any older, do we?

461
00:26:39.428 --> 00:26:41.668
We actually look exactly the same.

462
00:26:42.408 --> 00:26:46.388
So, yeah. Anyway. All right. So you've already

463
00:26:46.428 --> 00:26:47.508
heard about the

464
00:26:49.848 --> 00:26:53.218
evolution of PARP inhibitors and how we've

465
00:26:53.248 --> 00:26:56.508
been changing and how we think about

466
00:26:58.468 --> 00:27:00.428
PARP inhibitor development, and

467
00:27:02.408 --> 00:27:05.908
I want to really discuss and highlight the

468
00:27:06.008 --> 00:27:09.888
progress that we have made, but really the pitfalls that we

469
00:27:09.968 --> 00:27:11.988
have seen and have

470
00:27:14.928 --> 00:27:18.608
encountered in the clinic ultimately, but also to really show some promise as

471
00:27:18.708 --> 00:27:22.468
well and how we can move things forward ultimately in the

472
00:27:22.508 --> 00:27:24.448
clinic. So these are my disclosures.

473
00:27:25.368 --> 00:27:27.668
Many friends, many of you in this room, I think.

474
00:27:28.488 --> 00:27:30.308
All right. So for me as a clinician,

475
00:27:31.908 --> 00:27:35.448
really thinking about how we can raise that bar for all of our

476
00:27:35.488 --> 00:27:36.188
patients

477
00:27:37.108 --> 00:27:41.068
in the clinic. It's really about going beyond the usual

478
00:27:41.208 --> 00:27:45.128
suspects in terms of drugging the

479
00:27:45.168 --> 00:27:47.488
cancer lesions that we can truly go after.

480
00:27:47.498 --> 00:27:50.928
And I really do think that exploiting synthetic

481
00:27:50.938 --> 00:27:52.638
lethality will help us do that.

482
00:27:53.648 --> 00:27:57.628
And I say that because the focus of precision oncology for the

483
00:27:57.648 --> 00:28:01.208
past 20-odd years has really been on the gain-of-function

484
00:28:01.268 --> 00:28:04.828
alterations. The targetable ones like EGFR

485
00:28:04.888 --> 00:28:08.728
mutations in lung cancer, HER2 amplification in

486
00:28:08.788 --> 00:28:11.548
breast cancer, and that's great, and that's fantastic.

487
00:28:11.628 --> 00:28:15.608
But I really do think that to really raise that bar and to go

488
00:28:15.688 --> 00:28:19.628
beyond the usual suspects, we really need to go after the

489
00:28:20.248 --> 00:28:24.208
untapped space here. Right? And I do think that that comprises

490
00:28:24.268 --> 00:28:27.828
gain-of-function alterations like CCNE1

491
00:28:27.888 --> 00:28:30.288
overexpression or amplification.

492
00:28:31.427 --> 00:28:35.368
We have no approved drugs right now for patients with those

493
00:28:35.428 --> 00:28:39.288
alterations. And also thinking beyond BRCA1

494
00:28:39.308 --> 00:28:42.458
and BRCA2 mutations as well. Are there other

495
00:28:43.128 --> 00:28:46.268
tumor suppressor alterations that we can go after, right?

496
00:28:47.008 --> 00:28:50.788
And so I really do think that there is an untapped 71%

497
00:28:50.848 --> 00:28:51.728
space that

498
00:28:52.788 --> 00:28:54.628
remains to be drugged. And

499
00:28:56.328 --> 00:29:00.188
we are seeing some success, and I've laid out a few of these

500
00:29:00.248 --> 00:29:02.248
right now in synthetic lethality.

501
00:29:03.668 --> 00:29:05.208
What I consider hot areas,

502
00:29:06.108 --> 00:29:09.968
what I consider emerging areas, and what I consider novel areas.

503
00:29:10.008 --> 00:29:13.058
So hot areas I've put in there what Mark's already alluded to,

504
00:29:13.228 --> 00:29:16.648
POP1 selective inhibitors in HRR mutation

505
00:29:16.748 --> 00:29:17.288
cancers.

506
00:29:18.688 --> 00:29:22.308
Many of you are involved with the MTA corpus of PRMT5

507
00:29:22.328 --> 00:29:24.628
inhibitors in MTAP loss tumors.

508
00:29:25.448 --> 00:29:28.748
Tango, BMS, Amgen looking very

509
00:29:28.848 --> 00:29:30.168
promising based on

510
00:29:31.068 --> 00:29:34.468
Phase I/II data, and these drugs, I have no doubt,

511
00:29:36.208 --> 00:29:39.937
are showing great promise and hopefully great success in Phase III

512
00:29:40.028 --> 00:29:43.448
trials. And then also recently, the FDA

513
00:29:45.568 --> 00:29:49.538
provided fast track designation to the ATR inhibitor

514
00:29:49.568 --> 00:29:53.208
from Arteos in combination with low-dose irinotecan in

515
00:29:53.268 --> 00:29:54.328
patients who have

516
00:29:55.268 --> 00:29:59.038
ATM loss or negative cancers there, and that was

517
00:29:59.108 --> 00:30:03.088
based on a 50% response rate seen in ATM

518
00:30:03.148 --> 00:30:04.928
loss cancers across the board.

519
00:30:05.748 --> 00:30:09.668
And then as an emerging area, what I want to focus on really is in

520
00:30:09.728 --> 00:30:13.668
targeting CCNE1 aberrant tumors and share with you some

521
00:30:13.708 --> 00:30:14.468
data from

522
00:30:15.488 --> 00:30:18.708
the PKM1 study in combination with a Wee1

523
00:30:18.748 --> 00:30:22.618
inhibitorThere are also other emerging paralogs, if you

524
00:30:22.658 --> 00:30:25.558
like. So one helicase inhibitor in MSI tumors,

525
00:30:26.258 --> 00:30:30.038
SMARCA2 inhibitors in SMARCA4 mutation tumors that you'll hear about from

526
00:30:30.158 --> 00:30:30.618
Steve.

527
00:30:31.518 --> 00:30:35.418
KIF18A inhibitors of patients are actually selected for

528
00:30:35.498 --> 00:30:39.198
SEN tumors, for example, by undertaking whole genome doubling.

529
00:30:40.398 --> 00:30:43.718
BAS inhibitors in EP300 mutation tumors, and also

530
00:30:44.738 --> 00:30:48.598
again, what you will hear from Steve will be

531
00:30:49.018 --> 00:30:52.418
the activity, or at least pre-clinically, and the potential

532
00:30:53.238 --> 00:30:56.478
of ARID1B inhibitors in ARID1A mutation cancers.

533
00:30:57.978 --> 00:30:59.178
So ultimately, I think,

534
00:31:00.218 --> 00:31:03.658
we need to think about these synthetic lethal strategies.

535
00:31:04.238 --> 00:31:07.938
And as you know, as Mark has already alluded to, this has really been

536
00:31:07.998 --> 00:31:11.578
led by many different DDR inhibitor

537
00:31:11.618 --> 00:31:13.118
approaches that I've listed here.

538
00:31:14.258 --> 00:31:18.178
And as you know, it's been really facilitated through

539
00:31:18.238 --> 00:31:21.678
the discovery of novel precision targets enabled

540
00:31:21.718 --> 00:31:24.858
by modern CRISPR technologies and

541
00:31:24.938 --> 00:31:28.138
also progress that have been made

542
00:31:28.238 --> 00:31:31.278
in cancer genome sequencing technologies.

543
00:31:31.398 --> 00:31:35.218
And so that's really allowed physicians like myself to use

544
00:31:35.258 --> 00:31:38.998
biomarker-driven patient selection strategies to guide the clinical

545
00:31:39.078 --> 00:31:42.918
development and also to think about rational combinations.

546
00:31:43.878 --> 00:31:47.398
And the whole DDR landscape has expanded beyond PARP

547
00:31:47.438 --> 00:31:51.378
inhibitors, ATR, WEN helicase, Pol theta, the list goes

548
00:31:51.478 --> 00:31:55.278
on and on. And there are other agents as well in pre-clinical

549
00:31:55.378 --> 00:31:55.778
testing.

550
00:31:56.738 --> 00:32:00.568
And some of you may have already seen this slide that I've shown in the past, but

551
00:32:00.638 --> 00:32:04.578
here's a change here, because I really do want to share some hard truths, that

552
00:32:04.618 --> 00:32:07.518
there has been a recent fine-tuning of some

553
00:32:07.558 --> 00:32:11.518
DDR inhibitors as listed here. Several agents

554
00:32:11.538 --> 00:32:15.308
have been deprioritized by big pharma, by biotech companies,

555
00:32:15.378 --> 00:32:19.138
including the WEE1 inhibitor from AstraZeneca,

556
00:32:19.238 --> 00:32:20.008
dovrasirsob,

557
00:32:20.898 --> 00:32:22.098
DNA PK inhibitor,

558
00:32:22.978 --> 00:32:26.578
papirasirsob, and AZD-7648, the

559
00:32:26.638 --> 00:32:27.798
USP1 inhibitor,

560
00:32:29.218 --> 00:32:31.858
ATR inhibitors, and ATM inhibitors. Right?

561
00:32:31.958 --> 00:32:35.738
And so I think we need to take a step back, and I think we need to

562
00:32:35.818 --> 00:32:36.618
think about

563
00:32:37.498 --> 00:32:38.298
what are the lessons

564
00:32:39.278 --> 00:32:43.188
learned from all of these different experiences that we've had in the

565
00:32:43.258 --> 00:32:46.778
clinic. And for me, just looking back at the

566
00:32:46.858 --> 00:32:50.698
past 20 years and the development of all of these different

567
00:32:50.778 --> 00:32:54.278
agents, I think I can summarize the three key

568
00:32:54.378 --> 00:32:57.978
considerations for the optimal development of

569
00:32:58.098 --> 00:33:00.838
synthetic lethality strategies in the clinic.

570
00:33:00.867 --> 00:33:04.678
And some of you may think, "Oh, this is obvious," but I think it's important that

571
00:33:04.718 --> 00:33:08.578
we get down into the weeds of dealing with these three key

572
00:33:08.738 --> 00:33:12.218
challenges. Number one, the therapeutic index; number two,

573
00:33:12.838 --> 00:33:16.438
really developing a robust predictive biomarker strategy;

574
00:33:16.978 --> 00:33:20.738
and number three, to think about rational combinations that are also

575
00:33:20.778 --> 00:33:24.258
well-tolerated as well. So here are the three key considerations.

576
00:33:24.798 --> 00:33:26.658
Let's start off with therapeutic index.

577
00:33:27.658 --> 00:33:28.838
So

578
00:33:29.778 --> 00:33:33.438
all of you will know with these DDR drugs like PARP

579
00:33:33.478 --> 00:33:37.298
inhibitors, there are three really main mechanism-based toxicities.

580
00:33:37.358 --> 00:33:40.378
Mild suppression, not like chemo, but we do

581
00:33:40.518 --> 00:33:44.438
see some falls in the different lineages

582
00:33:44.858 --> 00:33:48.298
depending on the actual drug, as Mark already alluded to.

583
00:33:48.738 --> 00:33:50.998
We do see nausea, vomiting, and diarrhea.

584
00:33:51.048 --> 00:33:54.598
Again, not like chemotherapy, but it is something that we have to

585
00:33:54.618 --> 00:33:58.608
control. And also fatigue, usually mild, grade one to two

586
00:33:58.678 --> 00:34:02.378
fatigue. But I think it's really important to point out that there are key

587
00:34:02.418 --> 00:34:06.388
differences in the types and grades of toxicities between the different

588
00:34:06.398 --> 00:34:10.158
DDR drugs. Right? If you were to blindfold me and give me a taste test

589
00:34:10.558 --> 00:34:14.458
with the different DDR drugs, I could tell you if it

590
00:34:14.538 --> 00:34:17.087
was just mainly ANC drops

591
00:34:18.498 --> 00:34:22.319
and neutrophils. That's what we see with CHEK1 inhibitors, typically,

592
00:34:22.478 --> 00:34:23.958
like praxasertib.

593
00:34:24.839 --> 00:34:28.478
With ATR inhibitors, typically as a mechanism-based tox, we do see some

594
00:34:28.518 --> 00:34:31.859
anemia as the main mechanism-based toxicities.

595
00:34:31.998 --> 00:34:35.638
There are also differences in the types and grades of these

596
00:34:35.658 --> 00:34:39.328
toxicities between the different agents, but within

597
00:34:39.419 --> 00:34:43.399
each DDR class. So ultimately, the different PARP

598
00:34:43.438 --> 00:34:46.919
inhibitors, as Mark alluded to, have different types and grades of

599
00:34:46.958 --> 00:34:47.658
toxicities.

600
00:34:48.698 --> 00:34:52.538
In addition to that, some drugs do have off-target toxicities, like

601
00:34:52.678 --> 00:34:53.678
QT prolongation,

602
00:34:56.218 --> 00:35:00.058
elevations in LFTs. That was something we did see with rucaparib.

603
00:35:00.798 --> 00:35:04.758
And ultimately, the issue here is that these toxicities do impact

604
00:35:04.978 --> 00:35:08.198
the dosing in the clinic. They lead to drug holes, drug

605
00:35:08.218 --> 00:35:08.998
reductions,

606
00:35:10.338 --> 00:35:14.278
and ultimately potentially impact the monotherapy activity

607
00:35:14.287 --> 00:35:18.148
in the clinic. And the evidence for that pre-clinically is what

608
00:35:18.198 --> 00:35:21.738
Mark's already published on by Jemal Latel, and

609
00:35:21.978 --> 00:35:25.198
that will ultimately also have an impact

610
00:35:25.318 --> 00:35:28.978
on combinations, especially if there are overlapping

611
00:35:29.018 --> 00:35:32.738
toxicities. So what I would say, if there's just one point to take

612
00:35:32.778 --> 00:35:35.838
home, and that is really to judge each DDR agent

613
00:35:36.298 --> 00:35:39.198
individually based on the pharmacology pre-clinically,

614
00:35:40.018 --> 00:35:42.718
based on kinase screens, based on the

615
00:35:43.718 --> 00:35:47.378
on-target versus off-target effects, but also the clinical data.

616
00:35:47.448 --> 00:35:51.098
And don't judge them as a class, because each drug is

617
00:35:51.138 --> 00:35:52.778
extremely different from the other.

618
00:35:53.618 --> 00:35:55.408
So what can we do about these toxicities?

619
00:35:55.498 --> 00:35:59.238
I've laid out here the obvious things like the clinical measures,

620
00:35:59.338 --> 00:36:03.218
supportive measures like managing GI toxicities

621
00:36:03.258 --> 00:36:06.658
with anti-diarrheals, with anti-nausea pills,

622
00:36:07.238 --> 00:36:10.638
to think about dose modifications such as drug holidays

623
00:36:11.378 --> 00:36:15.318
or to really drop the dose. Right? But we of course try and avoid that.

624
00:36:16.098 --> 00:36:19.728
Maybe we should be avoiding the whole concomitant dosing piece and

625
00:36:19.758 --> 00:36:23.519
reallyThink about giving drugs in a maintenance setting if they're

626
00:36:23.590 --> 00:36:26.910
DDR agents, and that has led to success with olaparib

627
00:36:27.630 --> 00:36:30.850
in frontline ovarian cancer, and

628
00:36:31.230 --> 00:36:35.170
also pancreatic cancer. But I think more excitingly, there are

629
00:36:35.230 --> 00:36:39.150
improvements that are being conducted now and being done in terms of the

630
00:36:39.230 --> 00:36:43.040
drug pharmacology. Mark alluded to the PARP1 selective

631
00:36:43.190 --> 00:36:47.170
agents like sarubrutinib or pelacapronib or other agents such as

632
00:36:47.210 --> 00:36:48.310
from Duke-Street Bio,

633
00:36:49.210 --> 00:36:53.030
and several others. And there are some posters being shown at this

634
00:36:53.090 --> 00:36:56.690
ACR meeting as well that I would urge you to visit as well.

635
00:36:56.730 --> 00:37:00.490
And ultimately, the whole thinking behind this is that we can drive

636
00:37:01.170 --> 00:37:04.650
greater bang for your buck, if you like, to drive greater PK

637
00:37:04.690 --> 00:37:08.390
exposures with much, much less toxicity, and

638
00:37:08.470 --> 00:37:12.310
therefore really maintain high PK exposures of the drug

639
00:37:12.890 --> 00:37:16.780
that greater than 95% correlation inhibition, and

640
00:37:16.830 --> 00:37:20.570
really maintain that over time without any dose

641
00:37:20.590 --> 00:37:23.980
reductions, because it is something that we do see with the

642
00:37:24.010 --> 00:37:26.850
first-generation PARP inhibitors, which are all

643
00:37:26.910 --> 00:37:29.770
PARP1/2 inhibitors.

644
00:37:30.590 --> 00:37:32.650
There's a company called Sumitomo that have

645
00:37:33.550 --> 00:37:37.270
developed a liposomally encapsulated CHEK1 inhibitor to try

646
00:37:37.290 --> 00:37:40.470
and minimize the impact on the bone marrow.

647
00:37:40.490 --> 00:37:44.370
And with this, the thinking here is to increase tumor exposures and to really

648
00:37:44.410 --> 00:37:48.240
minimize normal tissue toxicities and to minimize

649
00:37:48.270 --> 00:37:51.430
the neutropenia that we do see with these drugs.

650
00:37:52.430 --> 00:37:55.570
With WEE1 inhibitors, these are being fine-tuned to dial out

651
00:37:56.150 --> 00:38:00.049
PLK1 and 2 inhibition. Examples of that are the drug

652
00:38:00.130 --> 00:38:03.550
from Dabio, which I'll touch on later in my slide deck.

653
00:38:03.870 --> 00:38:06.230
It's at Arestip, and also from Apria,

654
00:38:06.370 --> 00:38:08.210
APR-1051.

655
00:38:09.270 --> 00:38:12.130
As a clinician, I think we need to be a little bit more creative.

656
00:38:12.710 --> 00:38:16.690
I think gone are the days where we can just come in and combine drugs A

657
00:38:16.710 --> 00:38:19.230
plus B, and this is not just PARP inhibitors I'm talking about.

658
00:38:19.290 --> 00:38:19.600
This is

659
00:38:20.470 --> 00:38:23.310
with all classes of drugs. We need to think about

660
00:38:25.250 --> 00:38:29.030
schedules and dosing that's really focused on the biology and focused

661
00:38:29.090 --> 00:38:33.050
on preclinical modeling. And many of you in the audience can help us

662
00:38:33.150 --> 00:38:36.590
clinicians with that to think about alternating doses,

663
00:38:36.690 --> 00:38:40.210
intermittent dosing, if that's going to be the optimal schedule

664
00:38:40.670 --> 00:38:44.470
for that particular class of agents in combination, to think

665
00:38:44.550 --> 00:38:47.870
about gap scheduling for the optimal normal tissue

666
00:38:48.270 --> 00:38:48.930
recovery

667
00:38:50.190 --> 00:38:51.910
if there is overlapping toxicity.

668
00:38:52.710 --> 00:38:56.310
And if there is indeed a problem with toxicity, maybe use that to

669
00:38:57.010 --> 00:39:00.890
its greatest advantage. So there are now dual payload

670
00:39:00.930 --> 00:39:02.430
ADCs using

671
00:39:03.310 --> 00:39:07.290
exatecan payload plus an ATR inhibitor.

672
00:39:08.090 --> 00:39:11.970
There are drugs from Callio Therapeutics, there are drugs from Cross

673
00:39:12.050 --> 00:39:14.950
Bridge as well with HER2 targeting agents

674
00:39:15.070 --> 00:39:16.070
and

675
00:39:17.190 --> 00:39:20.010
TROP2 targeting ADCs respectively.

676
00:39:20.030 --> 00:39:23.830
And these are currently in pre-clinical or in early

677
00:39:23.870 --> 00:39:24.990
clinical development.

678
00:39:26.290 --> 00:39:26.470
So

679
00:39:27.370 --> 00:39:28.150
there are

680
00:39:29.430 --> 00:39:33.190
other considerations as well. Number two, as I mentioned,

681
00:39:33.810 --> 00:39:37.350
is really thinking about the predictive biomarker strategy.

682
00:39:38.010 --> 00:39:41.490
And I say that because I get referred many

683
00:39:41.590 --> 00:39:45.230
patients with these alterations, and I'll be honest, everyone

684
00:39:45.310 --> 00:39:46.190
thinks that

685
00:39:47.050 --> 00:39:50.930
any patient with a DDR mutation will respond to

686
00:39:50.970 --> 00:39:53.510
a PARP inhibitor. And that is not true.

687
00:39:54.240 --> 00:39:57.250
That is absolutely not true, and Mark has already shown some preclinical

688
00:39:57.350 --> 00:40:00.770
data suggesting that really there is a tiered system.

689
00:40:00.970 --> 00:40:03.630
Again, this is totally unpublished, totally my own opinion.

690
00:40:04.230 --> 00:40:07.350
So I can see all the cameras going up when I said that.

691
00:40:07.970 --> 00:40:08.510
That's funny.

692
00:40:09.430 --> 00:40:12.770
But for me, tier one would be BRCA2 right at the top.

693
00:40:13.210 --> 00:40:16.759
BRCA2 deletions, and then BRCA1, PALB2, RAD51C and

694
00:40:16.830 --> 00:40:20.350
D as tier one alterations. And then at

695
00:40:20.390 --> 00:40:24.010
bottom, bottom of the heap are really the ATM

696
00:40:24.070 --> 00:40:27.840
CHEK1, CHEK2, RAD54L that Mark mentioned

697
00:40:27.910 --> 00:40:31.750
earlier, and FANCL as well. And to me, these do not

698
00:40:31.810 --> 00:40:35.710
sensitize to PARP inhibitors because I don't think

699
00:40:35.750 --> 00:40:39.510
they really lead to an HRD phenotype in these cancers.

700
00:40:40.190 --> 00:40:44.010
So I think we need to be a little bit more thoughtful as to how we match

701
00:40:44.030 --> 00:40:44.590
patients

702
00:40:45.570 --> 00:40:49.390
with PARP inhibitors and other DDR agents as well because it does give us a bad

703
00:40:49.470 --> 00:40:50.310
reputation.

704
00:40:51.670 --> 00:40:55.430
But ultimately, as we're thinking long term, we really

705
00:40:55.510 --> 00:40:59.230
need functional HRD assays. We do have

706
00:40:59.290 --> 00:41:02.730
some approved HRD assays, but I think these are flawed.

707
00:41:02.770 --> 00:41:06.760
These are based on genomic scarring, and I'll come to why these are

708
00:41:07.230 --> 00:41:10.790
not the optimal functional assay in my coming slides.

709
00:41:11.550 --> 00:41:15.310
Number two, we need to remember, and this is stating the obvious, but all DDR

710
00:41:15.350 --> 00:41:17.790
agents have different mechanisms of action.

711
00:41:18.510 --> 00:41:22.150
So the truth is we need different predictive biomarkers of sensitivity

712
00:41:22.930 --> 00:41:25.350
for true synthetic lethality in a clinic.

713
00:41:25.830 --> 00:41:29.770
However, all trials use the same 15

714
00:41:29.990 --> 00:41:33.830
HRR mutations to select patients, and that means we're

715
00:41:33.850 --> 00:41:36.690
going back to all of these 15 alterations.

716
00:41:36.730 --> 00:41:40.500
And so if you enroll a patient with a tier two or three alteration,

717
00:41:41.130 --> 00:41:44.790
that's going to lower your chance of seeing a response, for example, to a PARP

718
00:41:44.810 --> 00:41:45.510
inhibitor.

719
00:41:46.550 --> 00:41:50.510
But ultimately, we need to think about the actual individual drugs as

720
00:41:50.570 --> 00:41:54.250
we think about the mechanisms. And so for me, under homologous

721
00:41:54.310 --> 00:41:58.230
recombination deficiency or HRD, that's where I would place your PARP

722
00:41:58.290 --> 00:41:58.870
inhibitors.

723
00:41:59.670 --> 00:42:03.390
But I would place the WEE1, the CHEK1, and ATR inhibitors probably

724
00:42:03.470 --> 00:42:05.800
under replication stress. So really different

725
00:42:06.610 --> 00:42:10.550
mechanisms to think about there. And then as you think about HRD, to

726
00:42:10.610 --> 00:42:14.330
really focus on the tier one HRR mutations and to

727
00:42:14.430 --> 00:42:17.950
also consider thinking about looking at these new

728
00:42:18.050 --> 00:42:19.900
functional HRD assays as well,

729
00:42:20.890 --> 00:42:22.950
one of which Mark already mentioned.

730
00:42:22.990 --> 00:42:26.798
And thenSo when you think about WEE1, CHEK1, and ATR

731
00:42:26.838 --> 00:42:30.698
inhibitors, really it's not about HRD anymore, but it's about replication

