1469
01:25:28.714 --> 01:25:32.684
So for a PARP inhibitor plus a TOP1 ADC agent,

1470
01:25:33.774 --> 01:25:36.684
our experience is that you want to be able to give gap scheduling.

1471
01:25:37.214 --> 01:25:39.054
So you want time for the bone marrow

1472
01:25:40.374 --> 01:25:44.354
damage caused by the ADC TOP1 to recover before you essentially expose

1473
01:25:44.394 --> 01:25:45.654
it to PARP inhibitor.

1474
01:25:46.534 --> 01:25:49.874
You can't really do that effectively on a dual payload with PARP and

1475
01:25:49.954 --> 01:25:53.614
TOP1. So I think there'll be some scenarios where it's fine and other scenarios

1476
01:25:53.654 --> 01:25:57.584
where you might want to have more ability to schedule, in which case, you might not

1477
01:25:57.614 --> 01:25:58.574
want them on the same molecule.

1478
01:25:58.934 --> 01:25:59.924
Sure. That's a good point.

1479
01:25:59.994 --> 01:26:00.204
And

1480
01:26:01.994 --> 01:26:05.654
there is a review out in "Cell" this week that actually covers

1481
01:26:05.714 --> 01:26:07.114
that concept of

1482
01:26:08.354 --> 01:26:09.134
gap scheduling.

1483
01:26:10.994 --> 01:26:14.384
Weren't you there first of all? Is that the one I owned the last of?

